## Description {#details}

This pass exposes codegen information to IR-level passes.

Every transformation that uses codegen information is broken into three parts:
<ul>
<li>The IR-level analysis pass.</li>
<li>The IR-level transformation interface which provides the needed information.</li>
<li>Codegen-level implementation which uses target-specific hooks.</li>
</ul>


This file defines #2, which is the interface that IR-level transformations use for querying the codegen.

<Link id="l00270" /><CodeLine lineNumber="270"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Underlying constants for &#39;cost&#39; values in this interface.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00271" /><CodeLine lineNumber="271"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00272" /><CodeLine lineNumber="272"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Many APIs in this interface return a cost. This enum defines the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00273" /><CodeLine lineNumber="273"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// fundamental values that should be used to interpret (and produce) those</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00274" /><CodeLine lineNumber="274"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// costs. The costs are returned as an int rather than a member of this</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00275" /><CodeLine lineNumber="275"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// enumeration because it is expected that the cost of one IR instruction</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00276" /><CodeLine lineNumber="276"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// may have a multiplicative factor to it or otherwise won&#39;t fit directly</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00277" /><CodeLine lineNumber="277"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// into the enum. Moreover, it is common to sum or average costs which works</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00278" /><CodeLine lineNumber="278"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// better as simple integral values. Thus this enum only provides constants.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00279" /><CodeLine lineNumber="279"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Also note that the returned costs are signed integers to make it natural</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00280" /><CodeLine lineNumber="280"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// to add, subtract, and test with zero (a common boundary condition). It is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00281" /><CodeLine lineNumber="281"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// not expected that 2^32 is a realistic cost to be modeling at any point.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00282" /><CodeLine lineNumber="282"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00283" /><CodeLine lineNumber="283"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Note that these costs should usually reflect the intersection of code-size</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00284" /><CodeLine lineNumber="284"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// cost and execution cost. A free instruction is typically one that folds</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00285" /><CodeLine lineNumber="285"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// into another instruction. For example, reg-to-reg moves can often be</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00286" /><CodeLine lineNumber="286"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// skipped by renaming the registers in the CPU, but they still are encoded</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00287" /><CodeLine lineNumber="287"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// and thus wouldn&#39;t be considered &#39;free&#39; here.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00288" /><CodeLine lineNumber="288" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272c"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">enum</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272c">TargetCostConstants</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00289" /><CodeLine lineNumber="289" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272ca89f768b1267e3083b4eb05b4ab77e717"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272ca89f768b1267e3083b4eb05b4ab77e717">TCC&#95;Free</a> = 0,     </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///&lt; Expected to fold away in lowering.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00290" /><CodeLine lineNumber="290" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272cae46c9eecc49bd2dc253c607e78a0fb86"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272cae46c9eecc49bd2dc253c607e78a0fb86">TCC&#95;Basic</a> = 1,    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///&lt; The cost of a typical &#39;add&#39; instruction.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00291" /><CodeLine lineNumber="291" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272ca022565d444ccf496c0414bccefbcd9c8"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#ac44f6b9fdbb5f9cc199f8329cb0b272ca022565d444ccf496c0414bccefbcd9c8">TCC&#95;Expensive</a> = 4 </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///&lt; The cost of a &#39;div&#39; instruction on x86.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00292" /><CodeLine lineNumber="292"><span class="doxyHighlight">  &#125;;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00537" /><CodeLine lineNumber="537"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// The cost threshold for the unrolled loop. Should be relative to the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00538" /><CodeLine lineNumber="538"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// getInstructionCost values returned by this API, and the expectation is</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00542" /><CodeLine lineNumber="542"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// deemed profitable. Set this to UINT&#95;MAX to disable the loop body cost</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00543" /><CodeLine lineNumber="543"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// restriction.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00544" /><CodeLine lineNumber="544" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/targettransforminfo/unrollingpreferences/#a21e7febf468c370793f606da5cd0e6fe"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">unsigned</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/targettransforminfo/unrollingpreferences/#a21e7febf468c370793f606da5cd0e6fe">Threshold</a>;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00545" /><CodeLine lineNumber="545"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// If complete unrolling will reduce the cost of the loop, we will boost</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00546" /><CodeLine lineNumber="546"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// the Threshold by a certain percent to allow more aggressive complete</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00547" /><CodeLine lineNumber="547"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// unrolling. This value provides the maximum boost percentage that we</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00548" /><CodeLine lineNumber="548"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// can apply to Threshold (The value should be no less than 100).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00549" /><CodeLine lineNumber="549"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// BoostedThreshold = Threshold &#42; min(RolledCost / UnrolledCost,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00550" /><CodeLine lineNumber="550"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    ///                                    MaxPercentThresholdBoost / 100)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00551" /><CodeLine lineNumber="551"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// E.g. if complete unrolling reduces the loop execution time by 50%</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00552" /><CodeLine lineNumber="552"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// then we boost the threshold by the factor of 2x. If unrolling is not</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00553" /><CodeLine lineNumber="553"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// expected to reduce the running time, then we do not increase the</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00559" /><CodeLine lineNumber="559"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">    /// The cost threshold for the unrolled loop, like Threshold, but used</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00713" /><CodeLine lineNumber="713"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Compared to the SW implementation, HW support is supposed to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00714" /><CodeLine lineNumber="714"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// significantly boost the performance when the population is dense, and it</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00715" /><CodeLine lineNumber="715"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// may or may not degrade performance if the population is sparse. A HW</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00716" /><CodeLine lineNumber="716"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// support is considered as &quot;Fast&quot; if it can outperform, or is on a par</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00969" /><CodeLine lineNumber="969"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The list of available load sizes (in bytes), sorted in decreasing order.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00970" /><CodeLine lineNumber="970" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/targettransforminfo/memcmpexpansionoptions/#a40b0398eaf424a49dd8511b70f024a10"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/smallvector">SmallVector&lt;unsigned, 8&gt;</a> <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/targettransforminfo/memcmpexpansionoptions/#a40b0398eaf424a49dd8511b70f024a10">LoadSizes</a>;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00971" /><CodeLine lineNumber="971"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00972" /><CodeLine lineNumber="972"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// For memcmp expansion when the memcmp result is only compared equal or</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00973" /><CodeLine lineNumber="973"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// not-equal to 0, allow up to this number of load pairs per block. As an</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00974" /><CodeLine lineNumber="974"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// example, this may allow &#39;memcmp(a, b, 3) == 0&#39; in a single block:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00975" /><CodeLine lineNumber="975"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   a0 = load2bytes &amp;a&#91;0&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00976" /><CodeLine lineNumber="976"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   b0 = load2bytes &amp;b&#91;0&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00977" /><CodeLine lineNumber="977"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   a2 = load1byte  &amp;a&#91;2&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00978" /><CodeLine lineNumber="978"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   b2 = load1byte  &amp;b&#91;2&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00979" /><CodeLine lineNumber="979"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   r  = cmp eq (a0 ^ b0 | a2 ^ b2), 0</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00980" /><CodeLine lineNumber="980" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/targettransforminfo/memcmpexpansionoptions/#a539af322cfe66dc65527d95ab8413d4e"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">unsigned</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/targettransforminfo/memcmpexpansionoptions/#a539af322cfe66dc65527d95ab8413d4e">NumLoadsPerBlock</a> = 1;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00981" /><CodeLine lineNumber="981"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00982" /><CodeLine lineNumber="982"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Set to true to allow overlapping loads. For example, 7-byte compares can</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00983" /><CodeLine lineNumber="983"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// be done with two 4-byte compares instead of 4+2+1-byte compares. This</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00984" /><CodeLine lineNumber="984"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// requires all loads in LoadSizes to be doable in an unaligned way.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00985" /><CodeLine lineNumber="985" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/targettransforminfo/memcmpexpansionoptions/#aabda91dbd651656d2eacb39607b14e9e"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">bool</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/targettransforminfo/memcmpexpansionoptions/#aabda91dbd651656d2eacb39607b14e9e">AllowOverlappingLoads</a> = </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">false</span><span class="doxyHighlight">;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00986" /><CodeLine lineNumber="986"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00987" /><CodeLine lineNumber="987"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Sometimes, the amount of data that needs to be compared is smaller than</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00988" /><CodeLine lineNumber="988"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// the standard register size, but it cannot be loaded with just one load</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00989" /><CodeLine lineNumber="989"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// instruction. For example, if the size of the memory comparison is 6</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00990" /><CodeLine lineNumber="990"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// bytes, we can handle it more efficiently by loading all 6 bytes in a</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00992" /><CodeLine lineNumber="992"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// separate blocks with conditional jumps for 4 and 2 byte loads. This</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00993" /><CodeLine lineNumber="993"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// approach simplifies the process and produces the comparison result as</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01317" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1317"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// A higher cost indicates less expected throughput.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01318" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1318"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// From Agner Fog&#39;s guides, reciprocal throughput is &quot;the average number of</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01319" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1319"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// clock cycles per instruction when the instructions are not part of a</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01369" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1369"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Represents a hint about the context in which a cast is used.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01370" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1370"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01371" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1371"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// For zext/sext, the context of the cast is the operand, which must be a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01372" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1372"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// load of some kind. For trunc, the context is of the cast is the single</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01373" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1373"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// user of the instruction, which must be a store of some kind.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01374" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1374"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01375" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1375"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// This enum allows the vectorizer to give getCastInstrCost an idea of the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01376" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1376"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// type of cast it&#39;s dealing with, as not every cast is equal. For instance,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01377" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1377"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// the zext of a load may be free, but the zext of an interleaving load can</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01378" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1378"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  //// be (very) expensive!</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01379" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1379"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01380" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1380"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// See \\c getCastContextHint to compute a CastContextHint from a cast</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01381" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1381"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Instruction&#42;. Callers can use it if they don&#39;t need to override the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01382" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1382"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// context and just want it to be calculated from the instruction.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01383" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1383"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01384" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1384"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// FIXME: This handles the types of load/store that the vectorizer can</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01385" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1385"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// produce, which are the cases where the context instruction is most</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01386" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1386"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// likely to be incorrect. There are other situations where that can happen</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01387" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1387"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// too, which might be handled here but in the long run a more general</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01388" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1388"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// solution of costing multiple instructions at the same times may be better.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01389" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1389" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#af84cce349a77262269fd3f6756f37a64"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">enum class</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#af84cce349a77262269fd3f6756f37a64">CastContextHint</a> : uint8&#95;t &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01390" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1390" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#af84cce349a77262269fd3f6756f37a64a6adf97f83acf6453d4a6a4b1070f3754"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#af84cce349a77262269fd3f6756f37a64a6adf97f83acf6453d4a6a4b1070f3754">None</a>,          </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///&lt; The cast is not used with a load/store of any kind.</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01556" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1556"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Calculate the cost of vector reduction intrinsics.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01557" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1557"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01558" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1558"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// This is the cost of reducing the vector value of type \\p Ty to a scalar</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01559" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1559"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// value using the operation denoted by \\p Opcode. The FastMathFlags</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01560" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1560"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// parameter \\p FMF indicates what type of reduction we are performing:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01561" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1561"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   1 Tree-wise. This is the typical &#39;fast&#39; reduction performed that</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01562" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1562"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   involves successively splitting a vector into half and doing the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01563" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1563"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   operation on the pair of halves until you have a scalar value. For</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01564" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1564"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   example:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01565" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1565"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///     (v0, v1, v2, v3)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01566" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1566"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///     ((v0+v2), (v1+v3), undef, undef)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01567" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1567"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///     ((v0+v2+v1+v3), undef, undef, undef)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01568" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1568"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   This is the default behaviour for integer operations, whereas for</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01569" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1569"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   floating point we only do this if \\p FMF indicates that</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01570" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1570"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   reassociation is allowed.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01571" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1571"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   2 Ordered. For a vector with N elements this involves performing N</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01572" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1572"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   operations in lane order, starting with an initial scalar value, i.e.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01573" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1573"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///     result = InitVal + v0</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01574" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1574"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///     result = result + v1</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01575" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1575"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///     result = result + v2</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01576" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1576"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///     result = result + v3</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01577" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1577"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   This is only the case for FP operations and when reassociation is not</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01578" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1578"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   allowed.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01579" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1579"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01580" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1580"><span class="doxyHighlight">  <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/instructioncost">InstructionCost</a> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo/#a421ee26483edf3fd0cd1dca34513f45e">getArithmeticReductionCost</a>(</span></CodeLine>
